<!DOCTYPE task PUBLIC "-//OASIS//DTD DITA General Task//EN" "generalTask.dtd">
<task id="table_create" xml:lang="en-US">
    <title>Task: Convert Range to Table</title>
    <shortdesc>How to convert a range to an Excel table.</shortdesc>
    <prolog>
        <critdates>
            <created date="2017-08-31"/>
            <revised modified="2017-08-31"/>
        </critdates>
        <metadata>
            <keywords>
                <indexterm>Table<indexterm>create</indexterm></indexterm>
            </keywords>
        </metadata>
    </prolog>
    <taskbody>
        <context>
            <note type="other" othertype="File"><filepath>Candyboxes.xlsx</filepath></note>
        </context>
        <steps>
            <step conref="../common/reuse_task_parts.dita#reuse_task_parts/File_Open">
                <cmd/>
            </step>
            <step>
                <cmd>Select a cell within the data range.</cmd>
            </step>
            <step>
                <cmd><menucascade>
                        <uicontrol>tab Insert</uicontrol>
                        <uicontrol>Table</uicontrol>
                    </menucascade></cmd>
                <stepresult>
                    <p>The dialog box <wintitle>Create Table</wintitle> appears. The address of the
                        range to convert is already present.</p>
                    <fig>
                        <title>Dialogbox Create Table</title>
                        <image keyref="candybox_table_create">
                            <alt>Dialogbox Create Table</alt>
                        </image>
                    </fig><note type="important">If your range has labels that you want to use as
                        column headers, check the option <option>My table has headers</option>. When
                        there no labels, then uncheck this option. Excel adds automatically headers
                        to each column with generic names: Column1, Column2, â€¦</note>
                </stepresult>
            </step>
            <step>
                <cmd>Click <uicontrol>OK</uicontrol>.</cmd>
                <stepresult>
                    <fig>
                        <title>Table Candyboxes</title>
                        <image keyref="candybox_table">
                            <alt>Table Candyboxes</alt>
                        </image>
                    </fig>
                    <p>The range is converted to a table:<ul>
                        <li>A table format (style) is applied.</li>
                        <li>Filter/Sorting buttons appear in each column heading.</li>
                        <li>The tab <uicontrol>Design (Table Tools)</uicontrol> appears, and here
                                you can see that the table has been given a default name like
                                Table1.</li>
                    </ul></p>
                    <fig>
                        <title>Design ribbon</title>
                        <image keyref="ribbon_table_design">
                            <alt>Design ribbon</alt>
                        </image>
                        <note type="notice">Depending on your screen width its possible that you see
                            some styles instead of the button Quick Styles (group Table
                            Styles).</note>
                    </fig>
                    <note type="tip">
                        <p>It is wise to change the default name to a meaningful name so that you
                            can work with the table more easily later. You do this by selecting the
                            name and then typing in the new name.</p>
                    </note>
                </stepresult>
            </step>
        </steps>
    </taskbody>
</task>
